The HMD database says Russian 70-year-olds' life expectancy (LE) is 10.65 years. Assuming that permanent stress is offsetting by top-quality healthcare and helthy lifestyle of Russian president, why shouldn't he live so? But I'm going further by assuming his LE term less a bit, such as 60 plus LE for 60-year-olds, which is 15.84, so it equals to 70 plus 5.84 years. Assuming 5.84 years ahead as the point of uncertainty, the probability of the issue is estimated as low as 0.6%. Thus let it be 1% because there theoretically other scenarios are possible.

Looking at recent events, the spiral of bad news for Putin seems to have slowed down. He is still in a notably worse position than previously, but will probably continue to hold on to power. 2023 is not that far away.

The fact that on 14 Oct he announced that his reprisals for the successful bridge attack "are no longer necessary and that the 300K troop mobilization will be complete in a couple of weeks" can be taken in two ways. It might mean that he recognizes that his military is ineffective, he needs a hiatus to restructure, and/or that he has become concerned about domestic reaction to the draft. Alternatively, it might suggest that he feels it prudent to start prepositioning and, perhaps, to begin looking for an off-ramp. Or both. No matter which, it brings closer in time whatever the ultimate reaction will be within Russia to the extent of his miscalculation. This reasoning would seem to warrant some increase in the probability of his being gone by 1 Jan 23. All of that said, however, no large increase in probability is justified because Jan 1 is, itself, getting closer.

That doesn't imply that the mobilisation efforts will have (enough of) a effect in Ukraine itself, but it makes a snap revolution somewhat less likely.

According to Levada Center polling agency, 77% of Russians surveyed this month said they approve of Putin’s actions as president. That's still a pretty strong number. It is also the biggest drop in Putin’s approval since 2018, when he raised Russian workers’ retirement age and sparked nationwide protests. https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/09/29/putins-ratings-drop-on-ukraine-draft-a78925 (contains a link to the poll for all you Russian readers out there.)

Analysis by Edward Luttwak published by the Hoover Institution (Sept 21). If I understand his thesis correctly, the only war termination strategy that achieves "the most durable form of peace" is exhausting the material resources and manpower necessary to keep fighting." He makes the case that neither country will run out of manpower at current rates and that only Ukraine can run out of materiel resources if left to its own devices. But since it appears the "United States has seemingly added Ukraine’s sustainment to its other entitlement programs", Ukraine won't run out of materiel resources either. So how will the war end? I think he says it must end by a negotiated settlement, an unsatisfactory way to end. When will it end? In my opinion, the only recent base rate applicable to the Ukraine war is Saddam Hussein's invasion of Kuwait in 1991. Both involved an attack across an internationally recognized border with the objective of annexing the invaded country, and both resulted in almost universal opprobrium, and kinetic military action. Even the USSR, which still existed, did not condemn the war against Saddam Hussein's Iraq, and they did condemn his invasion of Kuwait. In any case, most countries, even traditional enemies, did not support Saddam, and cooperated against him. The war did not end with the ouster of Saddam, although there was an abortive try, which failed due to lack of support and resources.

To my mind, there are various circumstances that would cause Vladimir Putin to cease to be the president of the Russian Federation on before January 1, 2023. These range from the position of presidency to no longer exist by then to Putin having to step down due to poor health to him being forced to step down by parliament, the judiciary or through an armed coup of some sort. Then of course there is the probability of death between now and then, from natural causes or following some sort of attack on his life.Coups are few and far between in powerful, developed countries such as Russia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_coups_and_coup_attempts_by_country#Russia). That gives us a near-zero prior probability. There are reports that suggest he has organised the security forces such that it would be very difficult to coordinate a military coup (https://www.vox.com/22961563/putin-russia-ukraine-coup-revolution-invasion). The same applies to a popular uprising (same source). This will also make it very unlikely that his life will be taken in an assassination attempt. While the probability is nonzero, I estimate it to be very low - let's say 1 per cent in a full year, and a fraction of that for the time between now and January 1.To my mind, the biggest threat to his presidency is his health. The annual mortality rate of Russian men is reported to be 39.1/1000 for 65-69-year-olds and 54.1/1000 for 70-74-year-olds. Putin will turn 70 early October. There are quite a few reports out there that suggest he may suffer from either Parkinson's disease or thyroid cancer. That may be so but we have not seen any evidence. The 'uncontrollable shaking' and his attempts to hide that from view (e.g., https://youtu.be/Xg3HgN11nG0 and https://youtu.be/SGZTNW-U8bw, respectively) may well be indicative of something but I think a diagnosis cannot be stated from these images alone (e.g., https://www.dw.com/en/putin-and-parkinsons-what-experts-say-about-his-health/a-61597476). The same applies to reports of a 'bloated face'. True, he doesn't look too well but if completely honest, I wouldn't have stated that unless I had heard somebody saying that (https://www.dw.com/en/putin-and-parkinsons-what-experts-say-about-his-health/a-61597476). And yes, he must be under tremendous pressure due to the war (from his perspective) not going well which must have all sorts of fallout that may be threatening to him. So my 'posterior' estimate for a Putin death from natural causes is simply the mortality rate for 70-74-year-olds. He's not 70 yet and he'll be a youngster in the 70-74-years-old bin. Had there been no reports or signs of bad health, nor any assumed pressure then I would have taken the mortality rate for the 'younger' bin for the ~5 months between now and his birthday and the rate for the 'older' bin for the ~3 months between his 70th birthday and the closing time of the question.What I am leaving out is the scenario in which bad health renders him unable to fulfil the duties of a Russian president and that he'll be 'nudged' to step down. I find this very difficult to assess; 'health' is something I have virtually no expertise in. What could happen? A stroke? A heart attack? It's suggested that in the US, the average probability of a stroke for 65-69-year-old men is 11.0%/10 years and 13/7%/10 years for men in the 70-74-year-old age bin (https://www.ninds.nih.gov/health-information/patient-caregiver-education/brain-basics-preventing-stroke). That's only for strokes. Would that render him incapacitated? Again, let's up the odds a bit by taking the higher number, for reasons of assumed pressure/stress and for not knowing the probabilities of heart attack or any other condition that would incapacitate him.Combining the probabilities gives us 1% probability of a coup/uprising, 5.23% probability of death from natural causes and an additional 1.3% for a stroke - all for a period of one year. Adjusting these for the partial year between now and January 1 gives us 3.41%, 0.89% and 0.65%, respectively. Let's assume these are all independent events (bad health and death probably aren't): that gives a probability of 4.96%.(PS the uncertainties in any of above dwarf the decimal-point estimates, I know)

While he may be demonstrating symptoms, and there are reports of his being visited by an oncologist, I'm not inclined to give that much weight until there's some sort of confirmation or detail, not least because it seems unlikely that even if he is afflicted by some cancer, that it will progress enough to force him out of office by the end of the year. It's a question to which I feel like the dart throwing monkey, so almost any percentage you put here, you can come up with a or even several reasonable sounding explanations. I always thought of the Russian power aparatus as a black box, and right now probably more than usually. I will writing here my thoughts about the probably most complex political entity in the world and as of writing this sentense I have now idea what will come out of this thought process. The first issue I trying to understand: Why is the Kremlin such a black box in the first place? As I understand it, Putin doesn't trust his own institutions, and in that he is hardly alone, I assume misstrust is actually quite rampant in this circles, I imagine it actually a quite fearful and often hostile environment to work or just to move around in. Nobody really knows for sure what are the others are up to, what allegences they have, who owns favors to whom, what are the hidden agendas, stuff like that. And my guess is that Putin is just much more skillful in this game than almost anybody else and that he is purposefully keeping that way, just to minimize the chances a potiential rival might threaten him. So nobody is really trustworthy and not really trusting anybody. Everybody can be removed from his or her position at any moment and is in servival mode trying to get as much as possible out of the system because the clock counting down while not knowing what time the clock actually showing. As a side effect of that, lots of vital information doesn't get passed along to the people in charge, cause it's quite assured that vital information at one point is going over the desk of somebody, who has an incentive that facts do not reach a decisionmaker higher up in the hierachy. I'm not wondering so much anymore that Russia's armed forces turned out to be a paper tiger or, tragically for the Russsian soldiers in Ukraine, a better fitting term: a potemkin army. At moment (in my estimate) Putin's biggest concern right now is to prevent that public opinion turning against him and the security apparatus and/or the armed forces (or parts of it) is then siding with demonstrators. I'm thinking of scenario like Romania, when Ceaușescu was overthrown. It can be safe to assume that the power balances within the kremlin between the various service branches and factions are right now quite volatile and is rearranging. Another open question is who is taking the (public) blame for that. In anyway it will be more difficult for Putin to shift the failure to some other officials, cause the whole invasion was presented as his idea, so I think nobody is keen to take the responsibility for it and trying shift the blame. And blaming the West for it, is also a harder sell this time. It also depends now what are the Ukrainians doing now as is seems that they are now getting the initiative. Are they trying to retake Donbass (likely) and Crimea (very much unlikely in my estimate, Russia might use that as justification for using nukes). My guess is, when Russia can get Crimea recognized as Russian and Ukraine giving up it's claim on it, that would be something Putin could sell to the Russian public as the goal he wanted to achieve in the first place. That is in my estimate at the moment the (most likely, but still miniscule) best case scenario right now: Ukraine gets Donbass and some kind of (limited) west integration, while Russia gets Crimea recognized as Russian. Probably still a hard sell for both sides (especially for Selensky). So right now I give it a speculative 43% that Putin won't be President of the Russian Federation by the end of 2022. I would be really keen what's the take you guys have. I definitely missed a lot to take into consideration and I'm curious to know what that might be. So as always: Thanks you in advance for your comments and critiques.

I answered this question a few days after Russia invaded Ukraine. I thought at the time that Ukraine was sort of on its own and thought the Russian army would roll to Kiev in a couple of days, securing Putin's political future. My update: I believe Russia is facing all-out war in 5 dimensions. (These are guesses; I have no security clearance.): 1. Physical/terrain: Getting worse now as the ground thaws. 2. Financial: We are seeing the maturity of finance as an effective strategic capability in modern warfare. Pretty incredible results. 3. Intelligence: US & NATO systems are likely feeding Ukraine non-stop. Ukraine has clarity on Russian moves; Russia probably can't see much at all. 4. Electronic warfare: I believe US & NATO are supporting Ukraine in a proxy manner, giving them hardware we program/control, but Ukraine operates, keeping operations limited to emanation from Ukrainian systems. How else could Ukraine get airplanes in the air against some of the best anti-aircraft weapons in the world? 5. Cyber: Again, I believe US & NATO are supporting Ukraine in a proxy manner. Russia probably sees Ukraine taking action, not knowing where the source code originates. Summary: Putin is staking his political future on success in Ukraine to return Russia to its former glory as a great power. I believe his quest is doomed and he's doomed with it because it's all-out warfare in the dimensions we can't see (points 3-5 above). But oligarchs still expect Putin to protect their wealth, Russian families want their soldiers home, the general public expects victory, and generals want out of the quagmire (either by winning or retreat). At this point, Putin can't deliver to any of them.

Looking at three main factors; external pressure, internal pressure and personal issues. Externally he does not seem popular, but many folks have continued to lead a country despite massive external unpopularity, and Russia has plenty of natural resources to survive a long time and a well running propaganda machine, so I don't think that weights much in the overall result. Internally it seems the country is mixed - among the people there are many that are ready for change, but their voice has long been silenced. Also internally are the others in power, military and oligarchs, who are going to feel an impact from recent actions. Whether that impact is enough to get them to apply pressure to Putin and how quickly that happens is the question. 2023-01-01 is only 10 months away, which seems relatively short. Were this a guess about 5 years from now, I would weight this pressure more heavily. Finally there are personal issues - whether Putin gets sick, decides to step down out of embarrassment, is removed by force, etc. This is what I predict to be the most likely cause of change here. starting above the crowd on this question. At this point I am making the assumption that the situation in Ukraine will not improve for Putin i.e., Russia will outright fail in taking control of Ukraine or it only does so at massive costs (continuing sanctions, increasing protests domestically, ...). I have no doubts that Putin intends to stay in power but, fundamentally, it is other people that are keeping him in power: the police that arrest protestors, the army generals that carry out his invasions, the oligarchs that toe the line. If the attempt to invade Ukraine becomes increasingly unpopular and looks like a failure, and crippling sanctions look like they are here to stay, will anyone have an interest in helping Putin hold on to power? The police can't just go on arresting people for ever, but people are likely to keep having reasons to protest. The army seems to have been mislead to the extent that, reportedly, captured Russian soldiers are saying they never planned to actually be at war, and they are now failing to achieve any important objectives. The oligarchs are looking at losing billions and the free access to the west that they enjoyed. However, there is no alternative to Putin at the moment. There are obviously no other major politicians, well known opponents like Navalny are dead, and the leadership around Putin seems weak (e.g., the intelligence chief he intimidated in the published meeting video). Could any oligarch try to make the jump, either in Russia or from abroad (Khodorkovsky?). Therefore, I am not going too high yet.
